statement.p:
 Let A = \left(
\begin{array}{cc}
 1 & 2 \\
 0 & -1 \\
\end{array}
\right), B= \left(
\begin{array}{ccc}
 3 & 7 & 6 \\
 2 & -1 & 5 \\
\end{array}
\right), and C= \left(
\begin{array}{ccc}
 0 & -2 & 4 \\
 7 & 1 & 1 \\
\end{array}
\right). Compute the following as efficiently as possible by using any of the Laws of Matrix Algebra:

 Let A =\left(
\begin{array}{cc}
 7 & 4 \\
 2 & 1 \\
\end{array}
\right) and B =\left(
\begin{array}{cc}
 3 & 5 \\
 2 & 4 \\
\end{array}
\right). Compute the following as efficiently as possible by using any of the Laws of Matrix Algebra:

li.p:
 Square the answer to (b) to get \left(
\begin{array}{cc}
 136 &135 \\
 60 &61 \\
\end{array}
\right)

Invert the answer to (a) to get   \left(
\begin{array}{cc}
 -7 &\frac{51}{2} \\
 4 &-\frac{29}{2} \\
\end{array}
\right)

 Multiply the answer to (b) times A to get  \left(
\begin{array}{cc}
 88 &49 \\
 38 &21 \\
\end{array}
\right)
